ur capacities and liabilities? Such questions gave birth to anthropology as an Enlightenment science. This book argues that it is again appropriate to bring “the human” to the fore, to reclaim the singularity of the word as central to the anthropological endeavor, not on the basis of the substance of a human nature – “To be human is to act like this and react like this, to feel this and want this” – but in terms of species-wide capacities: capabilities for action and imagination, liabilities for suffering and cruelty. The contributors approach “the human” with an awareness of these complexities and particularities, rendering this volume unique in its ability to build on anthropology’s ethnographic expertise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aHuman behaviorxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aAmit, Vered, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrving, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarsen, Tord, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchand, Trevor H. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapport, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRapport, Nigel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSkinner, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuski, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184